cs.CR, cs.LO, cs.PL, cs.SE, cs.CC

This paper is most likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category as it deals with checking cryptographic protocols. The use of formalism and the identification of necessary and sufficient properties of cryptographic primitives further supports this. 

The paper also involves logical reasoning and the use of formal methods, which suggests it could belong to the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. 

The use of a library of standard primitives and the focus on expressing actions and properties of cryptographic primitives suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. 

The paper also deals with the properties of intruders and the security of protocols, which could place it in the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves the analysis of cryptographic protocols, which could place it in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category, although this is less likely than the other categories mentioned.
